    reading: `The Assembly Line is where patterns are built. Not refined, not adjusted, not maintained — built. Building means overwriting a deeply grooved attractor state with a new one. It is the slowest work in this system. It is also the most important, because everything that comes after it depends on what was built here.

The process is organized around five stations, each with its own specific objective, verification standard, and graduation criterion. Progress is linear and earned: you do not advance to the next station until the current one meets its standard. Every session begins at Station 1, running confirmation reps on every previously passed station before advancing. This is not repetitive for its own sake. Attractor states erode. A pattern that passed last Thursday may have drifted by this Tuesday. The confirmation protocol catches drift before it gets built into the next layer.

The Proof Swing is the Assembly Line's governing concept. Before a ball is ever struck, the goal is to produce a full-speed downswing on camera that matches tour-caliber positions within 5% on Parallax. Not approximately. Within 5%. This standard exists because the Assembly Line's entire output is the Proof Swing: a verified, filmed record of a correct mechanical pattern. Without this record, "I think I've got it" is the best you can offer. With it, you have data.

The 5x5 standard governs station advancement: five consecutive reps within 5% of the tour model, verified on Parallax. The count resets on any failed rep. This sounds strict. It is strict. The reason is consolidation: a pattern that can produce four correct reps and then one failed rep is not yet stable. Five consecutive correct reps establishes a baseline of consistency that suggests the pattern has crossed the threshold from effortful execution to something closer to an attractor. It is not yet an automatic attractor — that requires far more repetition — but it is stable enough to build on.

The Snapshot Artifact explains why research comparing explicit (mechanical) and implicit (feel-based) learning approaches often unfairly disadvantages explicit learning. The studies measured explicit learners at their worst moment — the phase of maximum cognitive debt, when new positions are being consciously encoded and have not yet consolidated — and compared them to implicit learners at steady state. That is not a fair comparison. It is the equivalent of comparing a house under active construction to a house that was built decades ago and is fully furnished. Three major theoretical frameworks — Reinvestment Theory, Transfer-Appropriate Processing, and Predictive Processing — each independently recommend explicit construction as the correct first phase, because it is only by consciously encoding the correct pattern that the nervous system has something to automate.

The Dream House Protocol addresses the practical conflict between building a new swing and continuing to play golf. During the Forging Season, you are building the Dream House in the Assembly Line. On the course, you are living in the Old House — your current swing, with all its flaws. The protocol is: zero mechanical thoughts on the course. You play the Old House as well as it can be played. You do not experiment with Dream House positions on the course because they are not yet stable enough to withstand course conditions. They will break down, look terrible, and confirm your worst fears about the process. The course is not where construction happens. The Assembly Line is.

The J-Curve is the shape of performance during construction: a temporary decline before eventual improvement beyond the original baseline. Understanding the J-Curve in advance is essential, because the decline arrives early and feels definitive. Every golfer who has ever abandoned a swing change abandoned it somewhere in the bottom of the J-Curve — precisely when the process was working correctly. The bottom of the curve is not evidence of failure. It is evidence that the old pattern has been disrupted enough that the nervous system is no longer running it automatically, but the new pattern is not yet automatic either. This is the phase of maximum cognitive load and minimum performance. It passes. Staying in the process through the bottom is the entire game.`,
